h3. Summary

When filtering issues by issueLinkType the results are inconsistent when using the != and NOT IN operators.
h3. Steps to reproduce

1. Do an advanced search and compare the results when filtering all issues in a project and all issues in the same project excluding issues with a specific issueLinkType;
 2. Issues in the project can be checked:
{code:java}
project in ("Project A"){code}
3. Issues in a specific issueLinkType:
{code:java}
project IN ("Project A") AND issueLinkType = "relates to"
{code}
4. Now run with the != or NOT IN clause:
{code:java}
project IN ("Project A") AND issueLinkType != "relates to"
{code}
 5. Try by including an IS EMPTY clause:
{code:java}
project IN ("Project A") AND (issueLinkType != "relates to" OR issueLinkType is EMPTY){code}
h3. Expected results

The != or NOT IN operators should return the difference between the first and second queries.
h3. Actual Results

The values are inconsistent.

h3. Workaround

* For similar behavior to what would be expected results of an *"IS EMPTY"* or *"IS NOT EMPTY"* you can use the workaround noted in [JRACLOUD-72795|https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-72795] and do a *filter "!="* referance to a saved filter to exclude any issue with the set list of link types, like the following:
 * Create a saved filter including a list of all the current link types EXE:
{code:java}
saved filter = issueLinkType in ("all", "of", "the Issue Link Type Names", "as a comma separated", "List", "using Both the" "Outward Description" "And" "Inward Description")
{code}

 * Then in your final JQL:
{code:java}
Project = "Project A" AND filter != <filter_ID>{code}

h3. Issue Summary
Having a screen associated with the create issue transition for an issue type that can be linked to Epics, will fail when trying to create the issue inline in the new issue view.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
 # Add a screen which contains at least one field to the create transition of an issue type;
 # Add a validator that requires that field not be empty;
 # Create an Epic;
 # Try to create an issue inside the Epic using the inline creation;

h3. Expected Results
The screen associated with the create issue transition will appear to the user.

h3. Actual Results
The screen will not create, and the creation of the issue will fail.

Looking at the developer tools, you could the following request and error message:
{code}/rest/api/2/issue{code}
{code}{"errorMessages":["<error message configured in the validator settings>"],"errors":{}}{code}

h3. Workaround
Currently, the only workaround is to use the old issue view.
